title: perftest: set parallel executor and thread pool size separately

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: contributions welcome
labels.description: lower priority issues for the core ORT teams

body: In perftest, currently, there's only `-x <pool_size>` which activates both parallel execution plan and sets the session thread pool size. It would be good for benchmarking to be able to set these things separately. I suggest changing `-x <pool_size>` to only set the pool size (and mentioning that the default is the hw thread count) and add another flag `-P` (or whatever you like) that only enables parallel execution planning, with default being sequential execution plan.

title: Refine node selection logic in ShapeToInitializer optimizer
body:
ShapeToInitializer optimizer shouldn't replace 'Shape' even when the input shape is statically known (through shape inference) when -

1) The dimensions have one or more symbolic dimensions (logic added in the original PR #1159)
2)  The dimensions have all values known but one or more are "virtual" symbolic dimension value where the real value is only inferred  at inference run time. For example, in the case where a model has a graph input [-1, 20] feeding into a 'Shape' node, this node should not be converted to an initializer.

title: Allow building Docker container based on a different git repo.
body:
- Introduce Docker build ARG `ONNXRUNTIME_REPO`
  to allow building Docker container based on a different git repo.

Example docker build command:

```bash
cd dockerfiles
docker build -t onnx-runtime \
  --build-arg ONNXRUNTIME_REPO=https://github.com/jthelin/onnxruntime \
  --build-arg ONNXRUNTIME_SERVER_BRANCH=my-branch \
  -f Dockerfile.server .
```

- For consistency, also changed `dockerfiles/Dockerfile.arm32v7` and `dockerfiles/Dockerfile.ngraph` 
  to allow the same `ONNXRUNTIME_REPO` and `ONNXRUNTIME_SERVER_BRANCH` build arguments 
  as `dockerfiles/Dockerfile.server`. 
  The default behavior remains as before - build from the master branch in the central onnxruntime repo 
  if not overridden by specifying docker build args.

- Run `install_onnx.sh` script from the same location as `install_deps.sh`,
  rather than requiring it to be pre-installed into the `/tmp` directory in container.

  This fixes a file-not-found error when following instructions in the README file to do a docker build using `Dockerfile.server` https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/README.md

```bash
/onnxruntime/tools/ci_build/github/linux/docker/scripts/install_deps.sh: line 31: /tmp/scripts/install_onnx.sh: No such file or directory
```

- Add a basic `.dockerignore` file, to cut down the number of filles passed into the Docker build context.

title: Refactor CI pipelines, and add YAML NuGet package generation pipelines ( for CPU, MKLML, NoContribOps)
body:
Refactored the current build pipelines into templates so that common blocks can be reused.

Added new YAML pipelines for generating NuGet packages (including post-package tests). The 3 pipelines generate the CPU package, MKLML package and NoContribOps package.

title: make getkernelregistry not pure virtual function
body: GetKernelRegistry is designed to allow execution provider to have its own (per Type/Class) kernel registry, which is used to register its own kernels. This is not needed for "runtime" based eps, for example, ngraph, tensorrt, nnapi, etc. For these eps, the Compile API is the one used to get executable to run nodes.

title: Return better output shape for Loop with zero iterations
body:
Attempt to provide the correct rank for an output from a Loop node when there are no iterations instead of returning an output with an empty shape.

For a loop output (vs. loop carried dependency) the first dimension is the iteration count so will have a value of 0 and the output size will be zero. Use the rank of the matching subgraph output if available.

If the subgraph output rank is not available output a warning and use a rank 1 shape of {0}. We could possibly make a throw-away call to ExecuteGraph to get the rank from the fetches in that call if this proves to be insufficient.

title: Fix a bug that fused func manager in subgraph session state is nullptr
body:
**Description**: This fixes nullptr of fused func manager issue when running fused function inside sub graph session state

**Motivation and Context**
- The bug happens in running fused functions created IExecutionProvider::Compile inside sub graph, i.e. Scan, which causes crash.
- The problem is that FuncInfo is collected into main graph's session state, before sub graph session state is created.
- The fix is to share FuncInfo between main graph and sub graph.

**Description**: Propagate any errors from the parallel executor so that the behavior is the same as the sequential executor.

**Motivation and Context**
- Currently the parallel executor will swallow any errors/exceptions leading to poor usability
  - Changes expand on #1254 to provide a more comprehensive solution than just logging the errors. 

- Capture any errors (both failure Status or exceptions converted to a Status) during node execution by the parallel executor, and gracefully stop execution as soon as possible. 
- Return the failure/s to the InferenceSession level so they can be returned to the user. 
- Add unit test to validate behavior.
  - Created custom op to simulate an op returning an error status or throwing
  - Added ability to run custom op and use parallel executor to OpTester
  - Ran a manual test with a large model and a temporary hack to throw when executing a node in the middle of the graph to make sure exit was graceful.

title: Move CopyTensor out of IExecutionProvider interface.
body:
The change is a start to refactoring the IExecutionProvider interface a little bit.

Execution provider is a logical device, instead of a physical one. CopyTensor is only needed among physical devices. In our Tensor data structure, there's already a "Location" showing the physical device/memory information of a tensor, it's really not necessary to ask every Execution provider to provide implementation of CopyTensor. 

This change now,
1. Create a IDataTransfer interface, so that realy CopyTensor will be implemented as Data Transfer sub-classes.
2. Create a DataTransferManager (not thread safe) to carry all kinds of data transfer instances.
3. Register all kinds of data transfer instances when initializing InferenceSession before calling run.
4. Remove CopyTensor APIs from IExecutionProvider, and related implementation changes. 

As said, this is a start change. the following change (in separate PR) will be,
1. Refactor the OrtAllocatorInfo to not have duplicate information (say, id, memtype, etc).
2. The MemType should be real memory type related. Currently it's kind of abused by having something as 
OrtMemTypeCPUInput = -2,              // Any CPU memory used by non-CPU execution provider
  OrtMemTypeCPUOutput = -1,             // CPU accessible memory outputted by non-CPU execution provider, i.e. CUDA_PINNED
  OrtMemTypeCPU = OrtMemTypeCPUOutput,  // temporary CPU accessible memory allocated by non-CPU execution provider, i.e. CUDA_PINNED
  OrtMemTypeDefault = 0,  

btw, It's open to have data transfer registration exposed in inference session level.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Before this change, linux wheels were built on Ubuntu 16.04 and were renamed manylinux1 wheels in order to be uploaded to PyPI. However, they do not respect the manylinux1 policy and the result is that `pip install onnxruntime` install those none compliant packages on system that don't support them. Building on manylinux2010 docker image allow wheels built to truly be compliant with a manylinux policy in order to provide onnxruntime to a wider audience.

title: MLAS: NCHWc low-level changes
body:
Implementation of the MLAS changes for NCHWc convolution/pooling support. These changes adopt the blocking format used by MKL-DNN and other convolution libraries for better performance.

This PR splits the NCHWc changes to first push just the MLAS changes in isolation. A subsequent PR will include the ORT changes to integrate with the MLAS changes.

At this time, NCHWc is only supported for Windows/*NIX x64. Other architectures will be added in the future (there are stubs in order to successfully link on other architectures). The implementation has kernels optimized for SSE2/AVX/AVX2/AVX512.

There are multiple convolution kernel variants. There are kernels that accept NCHW input to handle the initial convolution into NCHWc space. There are kernels that accept NCHWc for pointwise, depthwise, or general convolution. All output NCHWc buffers.

There are pooling kernels for MaxPool and AveragePool (with/without include padding mode) and use NCHWc inputs and outputs.

There are also reordering routines to convert between NCHW/NCHWc buffers as well as reordering routines for the convolution weight buffers.

The MLAS unit test has been updated with code to call convolution/pooling with a variety of inputs.

title: Use the Loop body subgraph's rank for the iteration number and 'cond' values when creating the OrtValue instances.
body:
**Description**: 

Use the subgraph rank when creating the MLValue instance for the 'iteration number' and 'cond' subgraph inputs.

**Motivation and Context**

We generally consider both a rank 0 tensor and a tensor with shape {1} to be equivalent to a scalar, so a subgraph can potentially use either for the iteration number and cond inputs. Instead of inferring the rank from the Loop operators 'M' (max trip count) and 'cond' inputs, use the rank from the subgraph inputs. This will ensure the subgraph can be validly executed in case there are dependencies on the input rank.

Fixes some tf2onnx test cases.

title: python onnxruntime not using multiple threads for application of ml model

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: contributions welcome
labels.description: lower priority issues for the core ORT teams

body:
**Describe the bug**

Despite declaring the options 
```
options = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
options.enable_sequential_execution = False
options.session_thread_pool_size = 12
```

the application is only run on a single core.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux, Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): pip 
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.4.0
- Python version: 3.7.3

**To Reproduce**

```
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType
import onnxruntime
import numpy as np
import time
from onnxmltools import save_model
from skl2onnx.helpers.onnx_helper import select_model_inputs_outputs




y = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=100_000)
X = np.random.normal(y, 0.5, size=(25, len(y))).T.astype('float32')

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.95)

clr = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, n_jobs=12)
clr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Convert into ONNX format with onnxmltools
initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType([1, 4]))]
onnx = convert_sklearn(
    clr,
    name='classifier',
    initial_types=initial_type,
)
onnx = select_model_inputs_outputs(onnx, 'probabilities')
save_model(onnx, 'random.onnx')


options = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
options.enable_sequential_execution = False
options.session_thread_pool_size = 12


# Compute the prediction with ONNX Runtime
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("random.onnx", sess_options=options)
input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name


print('Starting prediction')
t0 = time.perf_counter()
pred_onx = sess.run(None, {input_name: X_test})[0][:, 1]
print(time.perf_counter() - t0)
```

onnxruntime is using 12 cores to apply model.
